<div id="review_14508943" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/14508943" />
    <a title="Gabriel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/780695-gabriel"><img alt="Gabriel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442598808p2/780695.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/14508943?book_show_action=true">Feb 04, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gabriel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gabriel" href="/user/show/780695-gabriel">Gabriel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer14508943" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16303242997303239247">Forget about all of this magical realism claptrap and comparisons to Garcia Marquez et al. <br/><br/>Donoso has written a sharpened stick to jab in the world&apos;s eye, according to the principles Poe expounded in his famous review of Hawthorne&apos;s &quot;Twice Told Tales.&quot; Poe&apos;s supposition that such &quot;unity of effect&quot; as is the author&apos;s goal cannot be sustained over the length of a work that takes more than one sitting to read is here completely refuted by Donoso&apos;s incredible sense of resonance. Everything here boun</span>
  <span id="freeText16303242997303239247" style="display:none">Forget about all of this magical realism claptrap and comparisons to Garcia Marquez et al. <br /><br />Donoso has written a sharpened stick to jab in the world's eye, according to the principles Poe expounded in his famous review of Hawthorne's "Twice Told Tales." Poe's supposition that such "unity of effect" as is the author's goal cannot be sustained over the length of a work that takes more than one sitting to read is here completely refuted by Donoso's incredible sense of resonance. Everything here bounces off of everything else, until the reader is uncertain that s/he hasn't just read the same thing twice. It doesn't how long it takes the reader to get through this book, because the same thing keeps getting played out in its various guises, without ever coming to any sort of resolution. <br /><br />The images, events, even the characters double, even treble until they waver in front of the reader's eyes. But the force behind it all is so great, and the set of images so primal, that despite all of this (potential) confusion, the reader has the sense that something of great importance has been communicated. <br /><br />The depth of thought behind this book is the mark of its genius. Everything converges until you see parallels that were not apparent before, but you see them as through an opened door that looks onto another just-opened door, that looks onto yet another just-opened door, and so on. Every character slowly melds until the shifty "I" of the narrator becomes clear-- not a trick, but the only solution to this multiplicity of self. <br /><br />And through those open doors, you see that infinity is actually constraint, that an endless nothing is no better than the most severe confinement. </span>
  <a data-text-id="16303242997303239247" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


