    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1884207259" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1884207259" />
    <a title="Jacob" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/35065355-jacob"><img alt="Jacob" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1527305913p2/35065355.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1884207259?book_show_action=true">Feb 07, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jacob" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jacob" href="/user/show/35065355-jacob">Jacob</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1884207259" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer453575388662964963">This was a difficult but constantly compelling and awe-inspiring book. Difficult primarily because of its narrator, whose identity is unstable. Compelling and awe-inspiring for its ceaseless and demented imagination.<br/><br/>Our narrator, Mudito, is a sort of dogsbody in the Casa, an adobe walled Convent populated by old women and orphans, full of labyrinthine hallways and boarded up doors. The Casa survives on the patronage of Ines Azcoitia, absent in Rome attempting to secure the beatification of her n</span>
  <span id="freeText453575388662964963" style="display:none">This was a difficult but constantly compelling and awe-inspiring book. Difficult primarily because of its narrator, whose identity is unstable. Compelling and awe-inspiring for its ceaseless and demented imagination.<br /><br />Our narrator, Mudito, is a sort of dogsbody in the Casa, an adobe walled Convent populated by old women and orphans, full of labyrinthine hallways and boarded up doors. The Casa survives on the patronage of Ines Azcoitia, absent in Rome attempting to secure the beatification of her namesake relative Ines, alternately reputed to have been a miracle-performing saint, a witch or perhaps something rather less extraordinary. <br /><br />The events described in the novel's blurb are just its centrepiece, coming in the middle of the book's three parts as a possible origin for Mudito. Therein he reveals his past as Humberto Peñaloza, a speech writer of humble origins for Jeronimo Azcoitia, husband of Ines. Jeronimo eventually charges Humbetro with overseeing the protection of his horribly deformed son. Or was Mudito in fact a baby abandoned at the Casa? What faith can one put in a narrator who apparently projects his identity onto others and onto inanimate objects?<br /><br />Donoso is not simply being difficult for the sake of it here. This is just one of the ways the novel keeps returning to a theme of myth making - of myths personal, superstitious, religious and cultural. Time and time again we see how stories divert from their actual origins, diverge further along speculative offshoots and converge again in strange new contradictory forms.<br /><br />Personal identity herein is not spared this fate. Liable from the first to be manufactured or distorted (as Jeronimo attempted to do out of protection for his son) or outright denied (as Mudito felt his had been by his humble origins as Humberto). It may then subsequently be hidden, forgotten and rewritten. One may even seek to become an Imbunche - this novel's twist on a hideous cave troll of Chilean folklore, whereby one seeks total sensory isolation from the external world.<br /> <br />This all comes in prose of constant, blazing intensity. Sentences sprint on across pages, packed with copious lists of this book's fantastic, grotesque and shocking contents. Dialogue is alternately rendered in quotation marks or weaved in and out the prose along elipses. The effect of this is often dizzying but somehow always incredibly immediate and vivid. </span>
  <a data-text-id="453575388662964963" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


