<div id="review_2921773863" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2921773863" />
    <a title="Adam" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1083458-adam"><img alt="Adam" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1545315869p2/1083458.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2921773863?book_show_action=true">Aug 22, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Adam" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Adam" href="/user/show/1083458-adam">Adam</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2921773863" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4272920194612871496">*big sigh*<br/><br/>No good read, no good review. It&apos;s equally possible that I failed to maintain the attentiveness needed (I did interrupt it for a few days to read Hamlet) and that this just isn&apos;t my jam. I can agree with the accolades while still asserting that I found the read unrewarding, can&apos;t I? I&apos;ll admit I may have suffered a full-blown episode of stupidity, but even flipping through it now I can&apos;t find much to make me care, not even the symbolic joints of paternity, monstrosity, history, politic</span>
  <span id="freeText4272920194612871496" style="display:none">*big sigh*<br /><br />No good read, no good review. It's equally possible that I failed to maintain the attentiveness needed (I did interrupt it for a few days to read Hamlet) and that this just isn't my jam. I can agree with the accolades while still asserting that I found the read unrewarding, can't I? I'll admit I may have suffered a full-blown episode of stupidity, but even flipping through it now I can't find much to make me care, not even the symbolic joints of paternity, monstrosity, history, politics, and religion. I'm resisting the temptation of rate inflation or talking myself into praising it more. Vivid, yes, nightmarish, yes, daring and difficult, yes yes, but in my eyes this noisome bird never leaves the ground. The sprawling sentences carom between the banal and the surreal and end up nowhere, despite the abundance of imagery. Maybe the time is out of joint and I needed this book years ago or years from now. Either way, I'm through with it today. </span>
  <a data-text-id="4272920194612871496" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

