<div id="review_22459847" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/22459847" />
    <a title="Eddie Watkins" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1131783-eddie-watkins"><img alt="Eddie Watkins" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1615322889p2/1131783.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/22459847?book_show_action=true">May 17, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Eddie Watkins" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Eddie Watkins" href="/user/show/1131783-eddie-watkins">Eddie Watkins</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1131783-eddie-watkins?shelf=chilean-fiction">chilean-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer22459847" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14058580762880714750">I read this quite a while ago and it&apos;s one of those books I keep telling myself to read again because I missed too much the first time through. All the memories I have of the book are probably false ones, but there is a general sense of elaborate deaths and elaborate reactions to deaths in somewhat tropical surroundings. There&apos;s also a sense of general bewilderment, but I do definitely remember that this is the book that made it very clear to me how much certain Latin novelists owed to William F</span>
  <span id="freeText14058580762880714750" style="display:none">I read this quite a while ago and it's one of those books I keep telling myself to read again because I missed too much the first time through. All the memories I have of the book are probably false ones, but there is a general sense of elaborate deaths and elaborate reactions to deaths in somewhat tropical surroundings. There's also a sense of general bewilderment, but I do definitely remember that this is the book that made it very clear to me how much certain Latin novelists owed to William Faulkner, or rather how much they loved Faulkner and couldn't help but be influenced. The Obscene Bird of Night is definitely Faulkner's Southern Gothic elaborated upon by a labyrinthine phantasmagoric Latin sensibility. I really need to read this again.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14058580762880714750" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


