<div id="review_2189600448" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2189600448" />
    <a title="Ricky Bosso" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24008063-ricky-bosso"><img alt="Ricky Bosso" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1513892544p2/24008063.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2189600448?book_show_action=true">Jan 17, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ricky Bosso" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ricky Bosso" href="/user/show/24008063-ricky-bosso">Ricky Bosso</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2189600448" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4620914854236412170">This book is a cave, and to descend into it is an intimate experience. Status and identity, if not the same, are shown for their tendency to change, to blur and intermix, to disappear in places. The Obscene Bird of Night is steeped in Chilean sentiment, and it is as personal as it is political.<br/><br/>It’s hard to forget, and I can’t think of anything really like it. Easily one of the best.<br/></span>

          </span>
        </div>


